%h3 Preface
.articles
  .article
    %h4 The Bible is the Word of God
    .copy
      %p Every single time you read the message of the Bible, you are hearing directly from God.
      %p For those who seek to hear from God, there is no simpler or more-direct way to do it than to open the Bible at random. It is desirable, of course, that one follow disciplines in reading the Bible, for these words were not written randomly or without context. Nevertheless, it remains true that when it is suitably applied, every single instance of reading the Bible in whatever language or form is a direct communication from God, even when the passage has been arrived at by means that, from our view, are random.
  .article
    %h4 Jesus Christ, the Word
    .copy
      %p Jesus Christ is the Word by Whom God created every created thing; nothing was ever created without Him. The basic message of the Bible is this: “Jesus Christ.”
      %p The Lord Jesus is in the beginning, at Genesis 1:1, and returns to be with us at Revelation 22:20-21. Jesus brackets the Bible, because it is His Bible.
      %p
        It is of His holiness the psalmists sang, and it is of Christ our Righteousness the prophets spoke. The Gospel is the point of the Law, “so that righteousness may be obtained by everyone who believes in God.”
      %p That “the incorruptible seed of the word of God” should be carried about on thin pages is a type of the incarnation of the Word, Jesus the carpenter from Nazareth.
  .article
    %h4 The Incorruptible Word of God
    .copy
      %p Therefore, just as Jesus is fully human, the Bible is fully book. Every translation suffers linguistic difficulties; every manuscript reflects the human; every book suffers decay. Yet the Bible is fully divine, just as Jesus is fully God. Every word is inspired by the Spirit; every Bible holy; every assertion eternally true.
      %p The Bible’s validity doesn’t depend on the opinions of men, neither those who support it nor those who oppose it. Debates concerning the Bible only ever happen in order to expose the agents of truth and the agents of falsity. Just as those who are destined for life believe in Jesus Christ, the Son of God, so also they believe in the Bible, the Word of God. The rest show themselves reprobate by insisting that Christ is just a-great-this-or-that, and that the Bible is only a book.
      %p By virtue of being the Word of God, the Bible is incorruptible. Languages come and go, media come and go, translations and versions, manuscripts and copies, traditions and targums, glosses and criticisms, they all come and go. But the Bible is here until the end, because it is the word of God.
      %p God watches over every Bible and every message of the Bible—wherever it is read, printed, or otherwise communicated—to jealously guard His word, rewarding those who respect and perpetuate it, and punishing those who set themselves up against it. The Bible, after all, concludes thus: “I declare to all who hear the words of the prophecy contained in this book: if anyone adds to it, God will add to his troubles the curses described in this book; and if anyone takes away any of the words in the book containing this prophecy, God will take away his share in the Tree of life, and in the Holy City—as described in this book.”
      %p Therefore the Spirit witnesses to us that when we read this Bible, we are reading the word of God. Amen.
  .article
    %h4 Inspired Manuscripts
    .copy
      %p The original manuscripts of the Bible were free from error, and entirely without reproach, every word being God-breathed. The Holy Spirit spoke by the ancient writers in a diversity of circumstances, and in several languages.
      %p This inspiration extends to every translation, copy, gloss, paraphrase, quotation, reading, or recording that is executed under the guidance of God, regardless of the weaknesses of the individuals who execute it.
  .article
    %h4 The Septuagint Manuscript Family
    .copy
      %p In the past, the Old Testament was translated to the Greek language, and God thereby began a new scriptural tradition. The Holy Spirit preserved particular idiosyncracies in this scriptural tradition, which were validated by God in the New Testament.
      %p It pleased God to preserve this validated manuscript tradition alongside the one in the Hebrew language, such that there are two that are used by the people of God. Historically, this family of manuscripts in the Greek language was known as the “Septuagint.”
      %p Being the incorruptible word of God, the Septuagint remains a rich and valid alternative scriptural tradition for the Old Testament.
  .article
    %h4 Brenton Septuagint
    .copy
      %p In 1844, an inspired translation of the Septuagint into English was executed from the original Greek language. This “Brenton Septuagint” is what has been included in <i>The Free Christian Scriptures</i> for the Old Testament.
      %p The glosses that the Brenton Septuagint indicates are set in a distinguishing font that doesn’t interrupt reading, but facilitates critical reading.
  .article
    %h4 The Masoretic Tradition
    .copy
      %p The scriptural tradition of the Old Testament in the Hebrew language, commonly called the “Masoretic,” has been used as the guide for indexing and reference devices, with provisions for tradition-specific extensions of the canon.
      %p Where it has been required for the purposes of harmonising the indexing and reference devices of the Masoretic with the Septuagint base, individual verses have been imported from the Masoretic and set with a distinctive font into the corresponding position of the text.
      %p The English verses of the Masoretic tradition have been based on an ancient inspired version, the King James Version.
  .article
    %h4 Westcott-Hort and Textus-Receptus
    .copy
      %p God having inspired the New Testament, He preserved it throughout subsequent manuscript traditions such that two valid manuscript traditions of the New Testament were evident.
      %p The tradition known as “Textus Receptus” collected legitimate glosses and explanatory devices, while the tradition known as “Westcott-Hort” sought the most-primitive form of the text.
      %p These two traditions, both being the incorruptible word of God, present two legitimate sources of editing precedents.
  .article
    %h4 The 20<sup>th</sup> Century New Testament
    .copy
      %p Basing mainly on Westcott-Hort, an inspired translation of the New Testament into modern English was executed in 1904. This edition, which was called “The 20<sup>th</sup> Century New Testament,” has been used for the New Testament in <i>The Free Christian Scriptures</i>.
      %p The original translation had paid special acknowledgement to some particular glosses found in the Textus-Receptus tradition. They have been incorporated into the text of <i>The Free Christian Scriptures</i> without differentiation. All other lacunæ with respect to Textus-Receptus have been retained.
  .article
    %h4 Creeds and Theology
    .copy
      %p This Bible has no textual-critical footnotes, that the word of God may stand in stark isolation and claim full contemplation, as long-time students of the Word would generally prefer. However, the <i>The Free Christian Scriptures</i> is also fit for those who are new to the Faith, as it includes the two traditional creeds of the universal Christian church, and the three accepted explanations of soteriology incorporating their traditional Bible references.
  .article
    %h4 A4 Paper Size
    .copy
      %p This copy of <i>The Free Christian Scriptures</i> is distributed as a PDF file with an active menu for navigating the books, chapters, and verses. This makes it suitable for use on computers.
      %p Further, the PDF is of the A4 paper size, which makes it suitable for printing, filing, and otherwise managing with common office stationery, which is generally geared for A4-size paper.
      %p Other A4 paper can be used alongside the Bible, such as for notes and illustrations, and then filed together with it, because of the standardising effect of A4 paper.
  .article
    %h4 Lectionary
    .copy
      %p Reading the Bible according to a pattern is not superior to reading portions at random, because the method and history of arriving at the word of God is entirely inconsequential. The word for the moment—such that “This very day this passage has been fulfilled in your hearing.”—can be part of an ancient lectionary or a page chosen at random.
      %p The random method is offensive to this age of the intellect, which is passing with all its empty vanities—for “Where is the intellectual? Where is the academic? Where is the modern philosopher? Has not God shown the intelligence of the world to be folly?”—and the ordered method only has narrow utility in applying the Bible to daily life, which involves unexpected encounters of Bible passages, casting lots, and reading favourite parts. —Yet whether we are reading a favourite part, or a passage from a lectionary, or a randomly-chosen part, it is still the appropriate word of God for that time, and should always be treated and applied as such.
      %p To facilitate an ordered reading of all the Four Gospels in one year, a lectionary has been included. The lectionary is based on actual dates of the days of the year, such that it is essentially a table of readings for specific dates on the year, rather than a traditional lectionary that distributes the readings over the traditional annual periods.
